     "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"For employees below age 55, the total CPF contribution rate is 37% of ordinary wages — 17% paid by the employer and 20% by the employee. Rates drop progressively from age 55, with the lowest tier (above 70) at a combined 10% (5% employer plus 5% employee)."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What is the CPF Ordinary Wage ceiling in 2026?",
     "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The CPF Ordinary Wage (OW) ceiling is S$6,800 per month from January 2026, up from S$6,300 in 2025. This means CPF contributions are calculated only on the first S$6,800 of monthly salary. Any wages above this amount are not subject to CPF contributions on the ordinary wage portion."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"Do part-time employees in Singapore have CPF?",
     "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. CPF contributions apply to all Singapore citizens and permanent residents earning more than S$50 per month, including part-time workers. The same age-based rate table applies. Contributions are calculated on the actual wages earned, not a pro-rated ceiling."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What happens if an employer makes the wrong CPF contribution?",
     "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Underpayment of CPF is a civil liability in Singapore. The CPF Board can recover the shortfall plus interest at 1.5% per month. Persistent non-compliance can lead to prosecution. The simplest way to avoid errors is to use CPF Board's online calculator or outsource payroll to a service that handles CPF submissions directly."}}
